<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.rollinsd.freeserve.co.uk" target="top">My Sonic the Hedgehog web site</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> | <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.rollinsd.freeserve.co.uk/STC-FAQ.htm" target="top"> My Fleetway Sonic the Comic FAQ </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> | <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.rollinsd.freeserve.co.uk/fanart.htm" target="top"> My artwork</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=linglingbolt>linglingbolt</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://liquid2k.com/lingbolt/spidey10x10.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(8/24/03 2:35 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5689.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.blindcrocodile.net/banners/willowhead60x60.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Help on drawing flames and explosions</span><hr size=1> OK, well... I'm actually not good at this myself (haven't practiced much), but I'll give it a shot.  Like anything, flames and explosions are three dimensional and made up of light and shadow.  Looking at some of your other art, you seem to draw primarily with lines (like a cartoon).  <br>
<br>
Try drawing thicker lines or multiple lines to give depth and volume.  The hottest part of a fire or explosion will generally be the brightest part, not only of the explosion but of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>the entire picture</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  If anything else is in the picture, the fire will be the main light source.  Anything facing away from it will be dark.  The darker it is (even if there is ambient light) the brighter/hotter the explosion or fire will look.<br>
<br>
Any fireballs or clouds of smoke will also be brighter where they are hotter. An explosion may have multiple centres as gas (or whatever) is blown away from the center and ignites.<br>
<br>
I suggest you look into pen-and-ink shading techniques, and examine photos of real explosions for ideas.  Hope that helps <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
